76561198365236399,Recommended,407230,30745032,Posted: 26 March,all,Awai,"Played Labyronia I and II and having played this, I enjoyed the story plot that ties in all three games together.This game differs drastically from the other two games in that you aren't exactly geared towards fighting monsters to level up. Rather, you are mostly on a hunt-seek to solve a mystery. Much like modern click and search games, this is like that, but in JRPG format, where you move everywhere, click everywhere, and try different actions with different characters. This may not be for everyone considering the amount of patience and memorization you have to have to perform certains actions. IE: immense backtracking to get an item back you didn't realize you needed or remembering which note/diary to pull up in front of a character. What was nice is that any monsters you killed previously does not respawn. With  the amount of backtracking at the later parts of the game, I appreciated this fact so I didn't have to re-kill all the monsters as I went back and forth.About the gameplay, it is somewhat linear in that you can progress in slightly different paths, but they all converge down to the same ending when you reach the end of that part. IE: you can complete one side quest before the other. Fight scenes are pretty rudimentary RPG mechanics. Not the best, but not the worse either. Some of the puzzles can stump you for awhile. I enjoyed solving them and even had to use a guide to figure out a few.One downside to the game is the vast amount of items you have. As noted earlier, you need to have a good memory or you will repeatedly scroll through your items trying to figure out which item goes to whom. I played the game without pausing too much inbetween so I had a decent rememberance of each item, but if you play the first few hours and then come back after a week or longer, you may struggle trying to remember everything. For a mystery RPG, there is a LOT of things to be found and to use. A few might even say too many, but considering the story plot, it does kind of make sense as to why there are so many items.Overall, it's a nice game to play. I did end up using the guide for the last 1/4 of the game, but I was progressing pretty quickly in the game in that I don't think I'd reach 10 hours of gameplay. 7.5/"
