,Recommended,407230,30806268,Posted: 28 March,all,nujumkey,"An excellent example of how creativity can build an amazing game out of an engine renown for bad RPGs like RPG maker. Combat is almost nonexistant, and frankly what little combat there is i found greatly dragged down the pace of the game.This is a murder mystery. Prepare to spend hours combing through every drawer, trashcan, and NPC you can find trying to find clues and puzzle pieces to keep the story going. At the beginning you are a prisoner charged with the crime of killing the king. To prove your innocence you set out a fugitive running around the castle trying to piece together information about the other possible killers and figuring out what happenned. The world is really built up and if you're willing to take the time and read all the books there is some really good stories in here. You get a really good idea through reading about the warring factions and groups, possible murder suspects and some of the waves the political struggle goes through. The grammer can have issues but untimately i got really into the story and the world, and i think it helps a lot that for 90% of the game there are no combat scenarios. Most of the game is through puzzle solving that makes use of the books and information you have similar to how a point and click game works. It's not what i normally expect seeing the RPGmaker tag.Admittedly some of the solutions are extremely contrived. At one point I needed an item from a cloaked wizard, who said he would help me if i found out what happenned to a girl named Indra. Turns out INdra hangs out in a cell in the prison, but when you talk to her she doesn't actually say her name. You just go back to the hooded guy and your character says he met with Indra in the jaul cell, but she never said her name and i can't tell where else we would have that information. Little things like that pop up everynow and again and it makes a walkthrough extremely neccessary to play the game (taking a bit of the fun out of it IMO). Also towards the end the game starts to really drag on as you encounter a barn and a labrynth with monster encounters. It's not a dealbreaker but it did annoy me that the appeal of the game - murder mystery puzzle solving - had been replaced by the most basic rpgmaker mechanics i had played so many times before.All in all though it's still a very cool game that makes really good use of the rpgmaker toolkit to do something unique and pretty fun."
